<|startoftext|>Headline:U.N. rights watchdog seeks U.N. report on Israeli settlement building
Content: "BRUSSELS (Reuters) - The United Nations Human Rights Committee is “very suspicious” of Israeli settlement plans because Israel has not always followed through with building and expansion of existing settlements that President Donald Trump warned would harm American interests, UN Secretary-General Antonio Guterres said on Thursday. “I’m very worried about the settlements and I think that’s precisely why there is so much media hype about it,” said Guterres, chairman of the 193-member body which is tasked with carrying out audits of all countries where land is confiscated. “We are very suspicious about the settlements and I think that they’re not transparent with it and why all the media hype” . Guterres has already visited to Jerusalem after the United States moved the U.S. embassy there in October from Tel Aviv and criticized Trump’s announcement to move the embassy to Jerusalem, which Israel captured in the 1967 Middle East war and annexed as the capital of its own government. “In my view, they [the Israelis] have developed this idea of building so many settlements so quickly to make up for all the land that the Palestinians were unable to get,” Guterres told a news conference. “The U.S. is not helping the Palestinian people to reach an independent state. But in terms of settling, in my view, the Israelis don’t follow their own plan.” The United States has called for a “two-state solution” to the Israeli-Palestinian conflict and for Palestinians to be allowed to build on land Israel captured in 1967 by the Arab League and other Arab countries. “The world is very divided on who will make up the two state solution,” Guterres said.  ",<|endoftext|>
<|startoftext|>Headline:UK's Brexit minister says Trump not pressuring his plans on EU exit
Content: "LONDON (Reuters) - Britain s prime minister has said President Donald Trump was not pressuring the Government to move its embassy in London from Tel Aviv. Michael Fallon said on Wednesday in a column in the Times of London newspaper that Trump s administration would not consider any foreign policy options before leaving for a new relationship with the European Union on the new year of 2017.  “They have not made the right steps on behalf of one new country, and in this case, the world,” Fallon said.  “And so I do say that they can be avoided with diplomacy and that is that they are not in the business of asking them to do things in the way that they have a mandate from the American voters.” Fallon was speaking on the sidelines of NATO Defence Week, during which Trump held bilateral meetings with NATO chief General Philip Breedlove, British Prime Minister Theresa May and American ambassador to the United States, Nikki Haley. Trump has repeatedly threatened to withdraw the United States from NATO, part of a growing shift toward global security. “Trump is not a leader in any sense,” Fallon said. “He does not have a majority.” ",<|endoftext|>
